 To align a row of divs to the right using flex in CSS, you can follow these steps:

1. Add `display: flex;` to the container element (e.g., .container) which holds the row of divs. This will enable flex layout for the container.
2. Use the `justify-content` property to align the items inside the container. Set its value to `flex-end` to align them to the right.
3. To make sure that all the divs take up the remaining space in the row, add `flex-grow: 1;` to each individual div.

Here's an example using HTML and CSS:

HTML:
```html
<div class="container">
    <div>Div 1</div>
    <div>Div 2</div>
    <div>Div 3</div>
    <div>Div 4</div>
</div>
```
CSS:
```css
.container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: flex-end;
}

.container div {
    background-color: lightgray;
    margin: 5px;
    padding: 10px;
    flex-grow: 1;
}
```

In this example, the container (`.container`) has its items aligned to the right (`.justify-content: flex-end;`) and each div takes up the remaining space in the row (`.flex-grow: 1;`).
